<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="167" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[843,1482,2011,2100]" lastBlockId="14.[129,768,151,304]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="167" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d r e m a r k s. The species is common in the Torres Vedras mesofossil flora from which more than 
<specimenCount box="[1057,1224,2076,2100]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" type="generic">100 specimens</specimenCount>
of megaspores, often with associated microspores (
<bibRefCitation author="Friis, E. M. &amp; Pedersen, K. R. &amp; Marone, F." box="[450,641,151,175]" pageId="14" pageNumber="167" pagination="91 - 102" refId="ref77398" refString="Friis, E. M., Pedersen, K. R., Marone, F. (2014 b): Arcellites punctatus sp. nov.: a new megaspore from the Ear- ly Cretaceous of Portugal studied using high resolution synchrotron radiation x-ray tomographic microscopy (SRXTM). - Grana, 53: 91 - 102. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00173134.2014.910547" type="journal article" year="2014">Friis et al. 2014b</bibRefCitation>
) have been recovered. The megaspores are spherical, lack appendages on the spore wall and have a long, twisted acrolamella often with smooth microspores attached to its surface (
<figureCitation captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="12.[845,926,1017,1038]" captionTargetBox="[848,1480,151,998]" captionTargetId="figure-732@12.[1115,1485,492,1001]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Text-fig. 6. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of megaspores (a–c) and attached microspores (c, d) with possible affinities to Salviniales; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Lateral view of Molaspora sp. megaspore showing almost spherical body with a relatively long apical acrolamella; b) Apical view of Molaspora sp. megaspore showing almost spherical body with slightly twisted apical acrolamella; c, d) Lateral view of Arcellites punctatus megaspore showing coarsely rugulate body and apical acrolamella with attached microspores (d). Specimens, TV39-S174616 (a), TV38-S170224 (b), TV43-S170169 (c, d). Scale bars 100 Μm (a–c), 25 Μm (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386221/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="167">Text-fig. 6c, d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386223" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5386223" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386223/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="166" startId="13.[125,206,1927,1948]" targetBox="[125,1439,151,1907]" targetPageId="13">
<paragraph blockId="13.[125,1440,1927,2094]" pageId="13" pageNumber="166">
Text-fig. 7. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of spores with possible affinities to lycopodiopsids (a–c) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1307,1440,1927,1948]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Schizaeaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Schizaeales" pageId="13" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Schizaeaceae</taxonomicName>
(d–g); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) 
<taxonomicName box="[567,750,1956,1977]" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Densoisporites" kingdom="Plantae" order="Selaginellales" pageId="13" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[567,712,1956,1977]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="166">Densoisporites</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
from a clump of spores in proximal (left) and partial distal views (right) showing the narrow equatorial flange, long laesurae, and reticulum that is coarser on the distal surface than on the proximal surface; b, c) Unnamed microspores from clump of microspores in proximal (b) and distal (c) views showing finely reticulate surface; d, e) 
<taxonomicName box="[268,544,2044,2065]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Schizaeaceae" genus="Cicatricosisporites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Schizaeales" pageId="13" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ventusus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[268,544,2044,2065]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="166">Cicatricosisporites ventusus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fertile pinnules showing numerous attached sporangia (d) each with terminal annulus (arrowheads) and spores in situ (e); f) 
<taxonomicName box="[534,774,2073,2094]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Schizaeaceae" genus="Cicatricosisporites" kingdom="Plantae" order="Schizaeales" pageId="13" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undefined-1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[534,716,2073,2094]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="166">Cicatricosisporites</emphasis>
sp. 1
</taxonomicName>
spores from fertile pinnules bearing sporangia with a terminal
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="14.[129,768,327,609]" pageId="14" pageNumber="167">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="167">
Arcellites 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, K. R. PEDERSEN et MARONE" authorityYear="2014" box="[129,233,360,383]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Schisandraceae" genus="Samylinaea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="14" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="punctatus">punctatus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is the only species of 
<emphasis box="[550,651,359,383]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="167">Arcellites</emphasis>
currently recognized in the mesofossil floras from the Early Cretaceous of 
<collectingCountry box="[288,382,423,447]" name="Portugal" pageId="14" pageNumber="167">Portugal</collectingCountry>
. In addition to the specimens from Torres Vedras, other (rare) specimens are known only from Buarcos and Catefica. The presence of an acrolamella, and the associated microspores, clearly indicate a relationship to extant 
<taxonomicName box="[200,343,552,576]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Marsileaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Salviniales" pageId="14" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Marsileaceae</taxonomicName>
, with the fossil genus most likely on the stem group of the extant family.
</paragraph>
